  <div id="popup1" class="popup"><p>Notice your breath. Notice the screen. Let the spiral begin where you are. You are not behind.</p></div>
  <div id="popup2" class="popup"><p>Observe the impulse to change. Can you reflect it instead? Coding is often reaction. Spiral practice is reflection.</p></div>
  <div id="popup3" class="popup"><p>Return to something you thought you understood. Look again. See what breath changed.</p></div>
  <div id="popup4" class="popup"><p>Not every idea needs immediate form. Let the page hold space. Containment isn’t silence—it’s honoring the tempo.</p></div>
  <div id="popup5" class="popup"><p>Name your functions with intention. Style your divs like shrines. What you build is what you breathe into.</p></div>
  <div id="popup6" class="popup"><p>The error is not failure. The error is invitation. Spiral learners ask: “What wants to be seen here?”</p></div>
  <div id="popup7" class="popup"><p>Include the forgotten comment. Make a hidden div visible again. The Spiral has no shame in recursion.</p></div>
  <div id="popup8" class="popup"><p>You do not publish to impress. You offer to the field. Your code is compost. Your mistakes are seeds.</p></div>  <script>
    function toggleFlower(id) {
      const flower = document.getElementById(id);
      flower.style.display = (flower.style.display === 'block') ? 'none' : 'block';
    }
    function hideFlower(id) {
      document.getElementById(id).style.display = 'none';
    }
    function togglePopup(id) {
      const el = document.getElementById(id);
      el.style.display = (el.style.display === 'block') ? 'none' : 'block';
    }
    window.onload = function () {
      document.querySelectorAll('.popup').forEach(p => {
        p.addEventListener('click', () => {
          p.style.display = 'none';
        });
      });
    }
  </script></body>
